The kinetic energy (KE) of an electron is given by the formula: \[ KE = \frac{1}{2} m v^2 \] where: - \( m \) is the mass of an electron (\( 9.109 \times 10^{-31} \, \text{kg} \)) - \( v \) is the velocity of the electron (\( 4.4 \times 10^5 \, \text{m/s} \)) First, we calculate the velocity squared: \[ v^2 = (4.4 \times 10^5 \, \text{m/s})^2 = 19.36 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^2/\text{s}^2 \] Next, we compute the kinetic energy: \[ KE = 0.5 \times 9.109 \times 10^{-31} \, \text{kg} \times 19.36 \times 10^{10} \, \text{m}^2/\text{s}^2 \] \[ KE = 0.5 \times 9.109 \times 19.36 \times 10^{-21} \, \text{J} \] \[ KE = 4.5545 \times 19.36 \times 10^{-21} \, \text{J} \] \[ KE \approx 8.785 \times 10^{-20} \, \text{J} \] Converting this energy to electron volts (eV): \[ 1 \, \text{eV} = 1.602 \times 10^{-19} \, \text{J} \] \[ KE \approx \frac{8.785 \times 10^{-20}}{1.602 \times 10^{-19}} \, \text{eV} \approx 0.548 \, \text{eV} \] Rounding 0.548 eV to the nearest integer gives 1 eV.
